Peel and finely chop the @Red Onion{1}(peeled and finely chopped) and @Garlic Clove{2}(peeled and finely chopped). Cut the @Mozzarella{1} into ½cm cubes. Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} and fry half the onion for about ~{5%minutes} until softened (keep the rest of the onion for your sauce). Add the @Panko Breadcrumbs{5}, @Dried Thyme{2} and half the garlic. Stir for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Take off the heat, put the mixture in a #bowl{} and add the @British Beef Mince{450%g} and @Tomato Puree{1%tbsp}. Season with @salt{1/2%tsp} and a good grind of @black pepper{good grind}. Mix together.

Use damp hands and shape the meat into small (ping pong sized) balls around each cube of mozzarella cheese.

> This is a perfect job for small hands, keep hands damp so the meatballs don't get too sticky.

Bring a #pot{} of water to the boil. Heat @oil{2%tbsp} in the frying pan on medium-high heat and fry the meatballs for ~{10-15%minutes}, turning occasionally, until browned on all sides and cooked through. Take them out of the pan and set aside.

> Be gentle when turning the meatballs, otherwise they might fall apart.

Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in the same frying pan and fry the remaining onion, garlic and @Italian Style Herbs{5} for about ~{4%minutes} until softened. Add the @Chopped Tomatoes{2%tins}, fill a quarter of one tin with water and add to the sauce along with the remaining @Tomato Puree{1%tbsp} and @Beef Stock Pot{1}, simmer for ~{10-15%minutes}. Add @?sugar{1/2%tsp}(if you have some).

Add the @Wheat Spaghetti{400%g} to the boiling water and simmer for ~{11%minutes} or until 'al dente'.

> 'Al dente' simply means it is cooked through but has a hint of firmness left in the middle.

Tip your cooked meatballs into the tomato sauce and gently mix together. Drain and divide the spaghetti between your plates, top with the meatballs and sauce and grate over the @Parmesan Cheese{4}.

> Cut the spaghetti into shorter lengths for very young diners.

> Adults may need a bib as well as smaller members of the family! It could get messy!